ite web|url=https://www.twincities.com/2018/03/26/vikings-legend-chris-doleman-working-way-back-after-surgery-for-brain-cancer/|title=Vikings Legend Chris Doleman Working Way Back After Surgery For Brain Cancer|website=twincities.com |date=March 26, 2018 }}</ref> On January 28, 2020, Doleman died from the disease at the age of 58.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001099609/article/hall-of-fame-de-chris-doleman-dies-at-age-of-58|title=Hall of Fame DE Chris Doleman dies at age of 58|website=NFL.com|publisher=National Football League|date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Footballstats |nfl=2500424 |pfr=D/DoleCh00}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{1985 NFL Draft}}\n{{VikingsFirstPick}}\n{{Vikings1985DraftPicks}}\n{{NFL sack leaders}}\n{{100 sacks club}}\n{{NFL1990s}}\n{{Vikings Ring Of Honor}}\n{{2012 Football HOF}}\n{{Pro Football Hall of Fame members}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doleman, Chris}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American football defensive ends]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Falcons players]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Vikings players]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Panthers football players]]\n[[Category:San Francisco 49ers players]]\n[[Category:National Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Pro Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Indianapolis]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from York, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Deaths from brain tumor]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football player}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|position=[[Defensive end]]\n|image=Chris Doleman 2013.jpg\n|caption=Doleman in 2013\n|number=56\n|birth_date={{birth date|1961|10|16}}\n|birth_place=[[Indianapolis, Indiana]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|2020|1|28|1961|10|16}}\n|death_place=[[Duluth, Georgia]]\n|height_ft = 6\n|height_in = 5\n|weight_lb = 289\n|draftyear=1985\n|draftround=1\n|draftpick=4\n|high_school=[[York City School District|William Penn]]<br />([[York, Pennsylvania]])\n|college=[[Pitt Panthers football|Pittsburgh]]\n|teams=\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] ([[1985 NFL season|1985]]\u2013[[1993 NFL season|1993]])\n* [[Atlanta Falcons]] ([[1994 NFL season|1994]]\u2013[[1995 NFL season|1995]])\n* [[San Francisco 49ers]] ([[1996 NFL season|1996]]\u2013[[1998 NFL season|1998]])\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] ([[1999 NFL season|1999]])\n|highlights=\n* 8\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[1988 Pro Bowl|1987]]\u2013[[1991 Pro Bowl|1990]], [[1993 Pro Bowl|1992]], [[1994 Pro Bowl|1993]], [[1996 Pro Bowl|1995]], [[1998 Pro Bowl|1997]])\n* 3\u00d7 First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[1987 All-Pro Team|1987]], [[1989 All-Pro Team|1989]], [[1992 All-Pro Team|1992]])\n* 2\u00d7 Second-team All-Pro ([[1990 All-Pro Team|1990]], [[1993 All-Pro Team|1993]])\n* [[List of NFL season sacks leaders|NFL sacks leader]] (1989)\n* [[NFL 1990s All-Decade Team]]\n* [[Minnesota Vikings|Minnesota Vikings Ring of Honor]]\n* 50 Greatest Vikings (2010)\n|statlabel1=[[Quarterback sack|Sacks]]\n|statvalue1=150.5\n|statlabel2=[[Interceptions]]\n|statvalue2=8\n|statlabel3=[[Touchdowns]]\n|statvalue3=3\n|nfl=DOL237308\n|pfr=DoleCh00\n|HOF=chris-doleman\n}}\n'''Christopher John Doleman''' (October 16, 1961 \u2013 January 28, 2020) was an American professional [[American football|football]] player who was a [[defensive end]] in the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He spent the majority of his career with the [[Minnesota Vikings]], and also played for the [[Atlanta Falcons]] and [[San Francisco 49ers]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Chris Doleman |url=http://www.nfl.com/player/chrisdoleman/2500424/profile |title=Chris Doleman, DE at |website=NFL.com |publisher=National Football League |date=December 30, 2013 |accessdate=February 6, 2014}}</ref> Doleman was an eight-time [[Pro Bowl]] selection and a three-time first-team [[All-Pro]], recording 150.5 career [[quarterback sack|sacks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/D/DoleCh00.htm |title=Chris Doleman NFL Football Statistics |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |date=October 16, 1961 |accessdate=February 6, 2014}}</ref> He is a member of the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] class of 2012.<ref>{{cite news |first=Kevin |last=Seifert |title=Chris Doleman makes the Hall of Fame |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/nfcnorth/post/_/id/38178/chris-doleman-makes-the-hall-of-fame |publisher=ESPN |date=February 4, 2012 |accessdate=February 6, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDoleman attended [[William Penn Senior High School]] in [[York, Pennsylvania]], and graduated in 1980. He spent a postgraduate year at [[Valley Forge Military Academy]] in 1981.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.profootballhof.com/enshrinement/2012/4/22/drafting-of-football-hall-of-famer-chris-doleman/ |title=Enshrinement \u00bb The Drafting of the 2012 Class \u2013 Chris Doleman |website=Profootballhof.com |date=July 17, 2012 |accessdate=February 6, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718084354/http://www.profootballhof.com/enshrinement/2012/4/22/drafting-of-football-hall-of-famer-chris-doleman/ |archivedate=July 18, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nDoleman played football collegiately at the [[University of Pittsburgh]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Snedden |first=Jeff |url=http://www.steelworldorder.com/2012/02/city-of-pittsburgh-well-represeted-in.html |title=City of Pittsburgh well-represented in Canton this summer |work=Steel World Order |accessdate=February 6, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222151942/http://www.steelworldorder.com/2012/02/city-of-pittsburgh-well-represeted-in.html |archivedate=February 22, 2014 }}</ref> He was a star linebacker and defensive end for the Pitt Panthers from 1981 to 1984. He ended his career at Pitt with 25 sacks which was good for third all-time at the time of his departure. That total still ranks sixth in the Pitt annals.\n\n==NFL career==\nDoleman was selected by the [[Minnesota Vikings]] in the first round (4th overall) of the [[1985 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/draft/history/fulldraft?season=1985 |title=National Football League: NFL Draft History |website=NFL.com |date= |accessdate=February 6, 2014}}</ref> He began his NFL career as an outside linebacker (OLB) in the Vikings' 3\u20134 defense, but for the 1987 season (Doleman's third season) the team decided to switch to a 4\u20133 defense, which resulted in him being moved from his spot at OLB up to the defensive line to play as a defensive end. The move paid off for Doleman, who recorded 21 sacks in the 1989 season, the highest total recorded that season and the fourth highest total ever.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/D/DoleCh00.htm |title= Chris Doleman Statistics }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/sacks_single_season.htm |title= Single-Season Sacks Leaders }}</ref> The 21 sacks in a single season was a Vikings record until [[Jared Allen]] recorded 22 sacks in 2011. Doleman later played for the [[Atlanta Falcons]] and the [[San Francisco 49ers]] before returning to the Vikings in 1999 for his final season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/D/DoleCh00/gamelog/1999/ |title=Chris Doleman 1999 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |date=October 16, 1961 |accessdate=February 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe was a first-team All-Pro in [[1987 All-Pro Team|1987]], [[1989 All-Pro Team|1989]] and [[1992 All-Pro Team|1992]]. He garnered second-team All-Pro selections in [[1990 All-Pro Team|1990]] and [[1993 All-Pro Team|1993]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/D/DoleCh00.htm |title=Chris Doleman NFL Football Statistics |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |date=October 16, 1961 |accessdate=February 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Doleman was elected to the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.profootballhof.com/enshrinement/class-of-2012.aspx |title=Class of 2012 |website=Profootballhof.com |accessdate=February 6, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202121940/http://www.profootballhof.com/enshrinement/class-of-2012.aspx |archivedate=February 2, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n! colspan=\"2\"|Games\n! colspan=\"4\"|Tackles \n! colspan=\"6\"|Interceptions \n! colspan=\"3\"|Fumbles\n|-\n! G !! GS !! Comb !! Tot !! Ast !! Sck !! Int !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! PD !! FF !! FR !! Yds\n|-\n! [[1985 NFL season|1985]] !! [[1985 Minnesota Vikings season|MIN]]\n| 16 || 13 || 113 || 0 || 0 || 0.5 || 1 || 5 || 5.0 || 5 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 3 || 0\n|-\n! [[1986 NFL season|1986]] !! [[1986 Minnesota Vikings season|MIN]]\n| 16 || 9 || 49 || 0 || 0 || 3.0 || 1 || 59 || 59.0 || 59 || 1 || 0 || 2 || 0 || 0 \n|-\n! [[1987 NFL season|1987]] !! [[1987 Minnesota Vikings season|MIN]]\n| 12 || 12 || 57 || 0 || 0 || 11.0 || 0 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 6 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[1988 NFL season|1988]] !! [[1988 Minnesota Vikings season|MIN]]\n| 16 || 16 || 58 || 0 || 0 || 8.0 || 0 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 2 || 0 || 0 \n|-\n! [[1989 NFL season|1989]] !! [[1989 Minnesota Vikings season|MIN]]\n| 16 || 16 || 94 || 0 || 0 || 21.0 || 0 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 5 || 5 || 7\n|-\n! [[1990 NFL season|1990]] !! [[1990 Minnesota Vikings season|MIN]]\n| 16 || 16 || 92 || 0 || 0 || 11.0 || 1 || 30 || 30.0 || 30 || 0 || 0 || 4 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[1991 NFL season|1991]] !! [[1991 Minnesota Vikings season|MIN]]\n| 16 || 16 || 101 || 0 || 0 || 7.0 || 0 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 1 || 2 || 7\n|-\n! [[1992 NFL season|1992]] !! [[1992 Minnesota Vi